    "summary": "The Grand Canal of China (constructed in its main form under the [[event:2154|Sui Dynasty]], c. 605–609 AD, extending earlier sections) is the longest artificial waterway in the world — a 1,776-kilometer canal system connecting Beijing in the north with Hangzhou in the south, linking the Yellow River and Yangtze River basins and providing the arterial transportation route that bound north and south China into a single economic unit for over a millennium. Emperor Yang of the Sui reportedly conscripted over 5 million workers to build the main sections in just six years — a construction program of pharaonic ambition that contributed to the Sui dynasty's collapse but created infrastructure the Tang, Song, Yuan, Ming, and Qing dynasties all depended upon.\n\nThe Grand Canal's strategic importance was immense: the economically productive south (the rice-growing Yangtze valley) could feed grain and tax revenues to the politically vulnerable north (the Yellow River plain and later Beijing), enabling imperial governance of China's vast territory. The canal system supported the rice economy of southern China, enabled the transport of silk, porcelain, and other luxury goods to northern markets and export routes, and allowed rapid troop movement in response to northern frontier threats. During the Song Dynasty (which taxed canal trade extensively), the Grand Canal became the commercial artery of the world's most sophisticated urban economy. The canal remains in use today — parts of it are still active commercial waterways — making it one of the few ancient infrastructure projects still serving its original purpose.",
    "wikipedia_url": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Grand_Canal_(China)",
